## 6. Phase 4: Dockerizing the Backend

### 6.1 Why Docker?

Docker packages your app + ALL its dependencies into a single **container** that runs identically everywhere — your laptop, Railway, AWS, anywhere.

Without Docker:
```
"It works on my machine" → breaks on server (different OS, Python version, missing libraries)
```

With Docker:
```
"It works in my container" → works everywhere (container IS the machine)
```

### 6.2 Dockerfile Anatomy — Line by Line

```dockerfile
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# STAGE: Base Image
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# Choose your base image. Options:
#   python:3.11        → Full Debian (1.0 GB) — all tools included
#   python:3.11-slim   → Slim Debian (150 MB) — most common choice
#   python:3.11-alpine → Alpine Linux (50 MB) — smallest but can break C extensions
#
# For ML projects, use SLIM (not Alpine) — Alpine breaks numpy/scipy/torch
FROM python:3.11-slim

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# STAGE: System Dependencies
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# Install OS-level packages that Python libs need
# Always combine in one RUN to reduce layer count
# Always clean apt cache at the end to reduce image size
RUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y --no-install-recommends \
    # OpenCV needs these:
    libgl1-mesa-glx \
    libglib2.0-0 \
    libsm6 \
    libxext6 \
    libxrender-dev \
    # OpenMP (parallel processing):
    libgomp1 \
    # Health check:
    curl \
    # Clean up:
    && rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# STAGE: Working Directory
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
WORKDIR /app

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# STAGE: Python Dependencies (cached layer)
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# Copy ONLY requirements.txt first. Docker caches this layer.
# If requirements.txt hasn't changed, Docker reuses the cache
# and skips pip install entirely → MUCH faster builds.
COPY requirements.txt .

# Install Python packages
# --no-cache-dir: Don't cache pip downloads (saves disk)
# CPU-only PyTorch: Saves ~1.5 GB vs CUDA version
RUN pip install --no-cache-dir --upgrade pip && \
    pip install --no-cache-dir \
        torch torchvision --index-url https://download.pytorch.org/whl/cpu && \
    pip install --no-cache-dir -r requirements.txt

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# STAGE: Application Code
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# Copy everything else. This layer changes on every code change.
COPY . .

# Create directories that the app writes to at runtime
RUN mkdir -p /app/outputs /app/logs /app/uploads

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# STAGE: Runtime Configuration
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# Document which port the app listens on (informational only)
EXPOSE 8000

# Health check — platform uses this to know when the app is ready
HEALTHCHECK --interval=30s --timeout=10s --start-period=60s --retries=3 \
    CMD curl -f http://localhost:${PORT:-8000}/api/health || exit 1

# Start command — Railway/Render set $PORT automatically
CMD ["sh", "-c", "uvicorn main:app --host 0.0.0.0 --port ${PORT:-8000}"]
```

### 6.3 The `.dockerignore` File

Like `.gitignore` but for Docker builds. Prevents unnecessary files from entering the container:

```dockerignore
# Version control
.git/
.gitignore

# Python
__pycache__/
*.pyc
.venv/
.pytest_cache/
*.egg-info/

# IDE
.vscode/
.idea/

# Environment files (secrets come from platform env vars)
.env
.env.*
!.env.example

# Runtime artifacts (created at runtime inside container)
outputs/
logs/
uploads/
audit_logs/

# Tests (not needed in production)
tests/
test_*/
*_test.py
test_*.py

# Documentation
*.md
docs/

# Large files that should be mounted as volumes
*.pt
*.pth
*.h5
*.onnx
*.pkl
*.safetensors

# Misc
*.log
*.tmp
```

### 6.4 Building & Testing Locally

```bash
# Build the Docker image
docker build -t my-backend .

# Run with env vars from .env file
docker run -p 8000:8000 --env-file .env my-backend

# Test it
curl http://localhost:8000/api/health

# Interactive shell inside the container (for debugging)
docker run -it --entrypoint bash my-backend

# Check image size
docker images my-backend
```

### 6.5 Multi-Stage Builds (Advanced — Smaller Images)

```dockerfile
# Stage 1: Build dependencies
FROM python:3.11-slim AS builder
WORKDIR /build
COPY requirements.txt .
RUN pip install --no-cache-dir --prefix=/install -r requirements.txt

# Stage 2: Runtime (only includes what's needed)
FROM python:3.11-slim
COPY --from=builder /install /usr/local
WORKDIR /app
COPY . .
CMD ["uvicorn", "main:app", "--host", "0.0.0.0", "--port", "8000"]
```

