## 14. Phase 12: Monitoring, Logging & Debugging

### 14.1 Structured Logging

```python
import logging
import json

# JSON-formatted logs (easier to parse in production)
class JSONFormatter(logging.Formatter):
    def format(self, record):
        return json.dumps({
            "timestamp": self.formatTime(record),
            "level": record.levelname,
            "message": record.getMessage(),
            "module": record.module,
        })

logging.basicConfig(level=logging.INFO)
logger = logging.getLogger(__name__)
```

### 14.2 Health Check Endpoint

Every production backend MUST have a health check:

```python
@app.get("/api/health")
def health():
    """Platform uses this to know if the app is running."""
    return {
        "status": "ok",
        "version": "1.0.0",
        "model_loaded": _detector is not None,
    }
```

### 14.3 Viewing Logs on Railway

```bash
# Via CLI
railway logs

# Or: Railway Dashboard → Service → Deployments → View Logs
```

### 14.4 Common Debugging Steps

```bash
# 1. Check if the server is running
curl https://your-backend.railway.app/api/health

# 2. Check recent logs
railway logs --tail 100

# 3. SSH into the container (Railway)
railway shell

# 4. Check environment variables are set
railway variables

# 5. Check disk space / memory
railway metrics
```

